### Cursor-Based Pagination

Use cursor-based pagination with `limit` and `cursor` parameters instead of offset, which becomes slow on large datasets. Cursors point to specific records, allowing consistent iteration even when data changes, and avoid the N+1 problem of counting total results.

```typescript
app.get('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const limit = Math.min(parseInt(req.query.limit) || 10, 100);
  const cursor = req.query.cursor || '0';
  const users = db.users.find({id: {$gt: cursor}}).limit(limit + 1);
  const hasMore = users.length > limit;
  res.json({
    data: users.slice(0, limit),
    next_cursor: hasMore ? users[limit].id : null
  });
});
```

**Common interview trap:** Using offset-limit pagination for all scenarios—it performs poorly at scale (O(n) complexity).

